{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 16:26:43.629515", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis — summary and findings\n\nExecutive summary\n- The overall network fabric (OSPF routing, DHCP, DNS, reachability between hosts and servers) is operational: I observed successful ping reachability across hosts and infrastructure with no packet loss.\n- I identified one clear anomaly localized to web_server_3 (10.200.0.6). This server is exhibiting elevated latency (~20–26 ms) compared with the other web servers (~1–3 ms) and is subject to an egress traffic-shaping rule (netem + tbf) on its interface. Interface counters also show the server is receiving a large volume of traffic but transmitting very little. The most likely root cause is local traffic-control (tc) configuration on web_server_3 limiting/adding delay to outbound packets (intentional test setting or misconfiguration).\n\nKey findings and evidence\n\n1) Network-wide reachability\n- Global reachability checks (ping matrix) show hosts, DHCP, DNS, load_balancer and web servers are reachable with 0% packet loss. Example: dhcp_server -> hosts, dns_server -> hosts, web servers -> hosts all returned OK in the reachability scan.\n  - This indicates OSPF advertisement and routing are functioning and basic IP connectivity is intact.\n\n2) Elevated latency to web_server_3\n- Ping from a client (host_1_1_1_1) to the servers:\n  - web_server_0 (10.200.0.3): avg RTT ~3.13 ms\n  - web_server_1 (10.200.0.4): avg RTT ~2.13 ms\n  - web_server_2 (10.200.0.5): avg RTT ~2.12 ms\n  - web_server_3 (10.200.0.6): avg RTT ~22.91 ms\n  - load_balancer (10.200.0.7): avg RTT ~2.98 ms\n- The reachability/ping matrix also shows web_server_3 RTT around ~21 ms from multiple hosts, while other servers show low RTT. This isolates the latency deviation to web_server_3 specifically.\n\n3) Local network config on server_access_router\n- server_access_router has the server farm network 10.200.0.0/24 on br0 (10.200.0.1) and OSPF routes to the host subnets. No routing anomaly seen in that device’s reported configuration. It appears to be forwarding traffic normally.\n\n4) web_server_3 local interface & traffic-control evidence (localization + root cause)\n- web_server_3 ifconfig/ip/route show:\n  - eth0: 10.200.0.6/24\n  - ip route default via 10.200.0.1 (server_access_router)\n- tc (traffic control) on web_server_3 eth0:\n  - qdisc netem root with \"delay 20ms\"\n  - child qdisc tbf with \"rate 1Mbit\"\n  - Output: \"qdisc netem 1: root ... delay 20ms\" and \"qdisc tbf 10: parent 1:1 rate 1Mbit ...\"\n\n  These tc rules directly explain the ~20 ms extra RTT to that host and a 1 Mbps egress bandwidth cap.\n\n- Interface counters on web_server_3:\n  - RX packets/bytes: very large (e.g., RX packets 288,608 bytes ~436 MB)\n  - TX packets/bytes: extremely small (e.g., TX packets 29 bytes ~2 KB)\n  - tc statistics also report only ~2 KB sent through the qdisc, confirming very low transmitted bytes observed.\n\nInterpretation / probable root cause\n- The primary abnormal condition is web_server_3 having traffic-control rules applied (netem add 20ms delay + tbf limit 1Mbit).\n- These local tc settings are causing:\n  - Elevated RTT for traffic to/from web_server_3 (+~20 ms).\n  - Very limited egress throughput from web_server_3 (1 Mbit), which aligns with the very low TX byte counters observed.\n- The RX >> TX counter skew on web_server_3 suggests it is receiving a lot of inbound traffic but sending very little response data (likely because egress is being rate-limited). This could produce application-level degraded performance (slow HTTP responses, timeouts) and may cause the load balancer to observe poor performance from that backend.\n- Possible explanations (for investigation): deliberate test/shaping configured on web_server_3, accidental application of tc rules, or a script/test that left shaping enabled. I did not find routing problems or packet loss; the issue is localized to the server’s local packet handling.\n\nLocalization (faulty device / component)\n- Device: web_server_3 (IP 10.200.0.6)\n- Faulty component: eth0 qdisc configuration (netem delay 20ms + tbf rate 1Mbit)\n- Supporting evidence:\n  - Ping averages ~22–26 ms to web_server_3 vs ~1–3 ms to other web servers.\n  - tc show output indicating netem delay 20ms and tbf 1Mbit on eth0.\n  - Ifconfig and tc counters: very high RX, very low TX and only ~2 KB observed sent through qdisc.\n\nImpact assessment\n- User-visible effects:\n  - Clients or the load balancer sending traffic to web_server_3 will experience higher latency and strongly limited throughput from that backend — resulting in slow responses or poor end-user experience when that backend is selected.\n  - Since the other web backends (web0–web2) do not show this behavior, overall service may be degraded only when traffic is directed to web_server_3.\n- Network/infrastructure:\n  - OSPF routing and inter-subnet connectivity remain healthy; this is a host-level performance/behavior issue rather than a routing fabric issue.\n\nSuggested follow-on diagnostic checks (no mitigation performed)\n- Confirm why tc rules were configured on web_server_3:\n  - Investigate local configuration management/automation (scripts, systemd units, cloud-init, Ansible playbooks) that could have applied netem/tbf.\n- Inspect application logs on web_server_3 (web server access/error logs) to confirm whether responses are being generated and queued/dropped, or if the application itself is not responding.\n- Check load_balancer backend health/distribution to see how much traffic is being sent to web_server_3 vs other backends (to confirm RX volume reason).\n- Run a throughput test (iperf) between load_balancer and web_server_3 to quantify the bandwidth cap; run the same to other web servers for comparison.\n- Check iptables or other packet filters on web_server_3 that might interact with tc or limit outgoing connections.\n\nConclusion\n- The network fabric and routing appear healthy; the anomaly is host-local to web_server_3.\n- Root cause (most likely): deliberate/accidental traffic-control rules (netem delay 20ms and tbf 1Mbit) on web_server_3's eth0 causing elevated latency and low egress throughput. This explains the observed symptoms (higher RTT, limited TX, large RX).\n- Next steps should focus on confirming why tc is present and whether it was intended; I can perform additional targeted checks (iperf tests, load balancer backend status, system/service unit inspection, logs) if you want me to gather more evidence.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 12483, "output_tokens": 3030, "total_tokens": 15513, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 11904}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1472}}}
